name: octane, 2,7-dimethyl-
Reason: The basic structure for octanes is n-octane, with a melting point of -57°C. A methyl group typically raises the melting point due to increased molecular weight; however, it can also lower the melting point by disrupting the optimal packing arrangement of the hydrocarbon chain and creating a less symmetric molecule, which reduces intermolecular van der Waals forces. The effect of adding two methyl groups at the 2nd and 7th positions in 2,7-dimethyl octane will slightly reduce the symmetry and alter packing compared to n-octane. The influence of each methyl group might shift the melting point by approximately +1°C due to increased molecular weight, countered by -3°C for the packing disruption.
